Why the same frontend bugs keep coming back
Press enter or click to view image in full size

You change a setting, save it, and the screen it controls still shows the old value until you reload. Small bug. You fix it in an afternoon.
But you’ve been here before. When you built that feature, you kept finding places where the same value had to be kept in sync (the panel, the dashboard, the cached copy), and you wired each one up as you found it. You tested it. You were fairly sure you’d got them all. Then QA found one you’d missed. You fixed it. A week later a path you never thought about was found and reported by a user.
That’s the part that wears on you. Not any single bug; they’re small. It’s that they never stop, and the only thing keeping the system in sync is you.
The bug is local. The fix is local. The coordination cost is systemic.
I call this the coordination tax. Unlike most technical debt, you never chose this one: it’s built into the architecture, and it comes due with every change, because one piece of truth lives in more than one place. A dashboard projecting the wrong data, stale UI in a panel, settings that aren’t applied as expected: these bugs are all related. They’re a single category, one cause with a handful of symptoms.
Where the tax comes from
A user interface has one job: take some underlying truth (what’s selected, what’s loading, what the user typed) and put it on the screen. The truth changes; the screen follows. There’s a phrase for this. The view is a function of the state: view = f(state). It's the idea Elm is built on, and the mental model React made popular.
Many frontends aren’t built as one truth projected many ways. They’re built as a graph of objects: a component holds a service, the service holds another service, each one keeping its own copy of whatever it needs. So the same fact ends up stored in several places: once in the list, once in the panel, once in a cache. And now the job isn’t projection anymore. It’s synchronization.
One piece of truth, living in more than one place.
Call each place that holds it an owner. When a fact has one owner, there’s nothing to keep in sync. The screen just reads it. When it has two, you’ve signed a standing obligation: every time the fact changes, every owner has to be updated, on every path, or they drift. The rule that the owners must agree is an invariant, something that’s supposed to be true at every moment, no matter what the app does. Here, nothing enforces it; it holds only as long as the developer remembers to, and once the app grows, tracking down every case for every change becomes impossible.
This is not a universal claim. Plenty of frontend problems aren’t this one: layout, animation, accessibility, raw rendering speed all have their own difficulties. But this category of bug, the one that keeps coming back, is exactly this, and it will keep coming back as long as a truth has more than one owner.
The four forms
It shows up in four shapes. They look different on the surface, a different fix each time, but underneath they are the same bug: multiple writable owners of one fact.
Every example lives in the same ordinary app: a list of items, a detail panel for the selected one, and a settings store for preferences. Nothing exotic.
For each: the broken code, the patch you’d actually write, and the tell (what the patch added, and what it left in place).
Manual fan-out
The selected item drives three things: the list highlight, the detail panel, and a selection cache used elsewhere. They’re separate owners, so selecting has to write to all three.
function selectItem(itemId: string): void {
listView.highlight(itemId);
detailPanel.show(itemId);
selectionCache.set(itemId);
}Now a second path appears, clearing the selection from a button somewhere else in the tree:
function clearSelection(): void {
listView.clearHighlight();
detailPanel.hide();
// forgot: selectionCache is never cleared
}Clear the selection, and the cache still holds the old ID. Something downstream reads it and acts on an item the user already dismissed. The patch:
function clearSelection(): void {
listView.clearHighlight();
detailPanel.hide();
selectionCache.clear(); // the fix
}The tell: the patch works. This is synchronization across copies: you didn’t remove an owner, you added a line that updates one more of them. Every new path that touches selection has to remember the same rule, or it drifts.
Missed-sync
The settings store owns the sort order. The list reads it once, at mount.
function initList(): void {
const order = settingsStore.getSortOrder();
listView.render(items, order);
}The user opens settings, changes the sort order, saves. The store updates correctly. The list, already mounted, never hears about it. The patch adds a subscription:
function initList(): void {
const order = settingsStore.getSortOrder();
listView.render(items, order); settingsStore.onChange((next) => {
listView.render(items, next.sortOrder); // the fix
});
}
The tell: one owner changed correctly; the other was never told. This is synchronization by notification. The patch doesn’t remove the second owner; it strings a wire between the two, a subscription to carry changes from one to the other. Two states that should have been one, now joined by a wire that has to be remembered.
Dodge
Saving settings is async. Right after saving, you restore the panel, which reads the freshly-saved value back from the store.
function saveAndRestore(settings: Settings): void {
settingsStore.save(settings); // async, not awaited
restorePanel(); // reads the store, too early
}function restorePanel(): void {
const settings = settingsStore.getCurrent();
detailPanel.applyDefaults(settings.defaultItemId);
}
The restore reads the store before the save resolves, so it applies stale defaults. The fix:
async function saveAndRestore(settings: Settings): Promise<void> {
await settingsStore.save(settings); // the fix
restorePanel();
}The tell: the patch changed timing, not structure. This is synchronization across time, and the fix is a timing dodge. The panel’s copy and the store’s still hold different values. You’ve just arranged not to be looking at the moment they disagree. It’s the most deceptive of the four, because it feels like a fix and it genuinely stops the bug. It stops it by making you careful about when you look.
Shape-reconcile
Settings are saved as JSON. The live panel expects a hydrated object with methods and resolved references. Same truth, two representations.
function restoreFromSaved(saved: SavedSettings): void {
detailPanel.applyConfig(saved.config); // raw JSON where a live object is expected
}The panel chokes, or quietly misreads fields, because saved.config is a flat blob and the panel was written against the rich runtime shape. The patch adds a translation:
function restoreFromSaved(saved: SavedSettings): void {
const config = hydrateConfig(saved.config); // the fix: JSON → live object
detailPanel.applyConfig(config);
}The tell: both values describe the same thing; the owners just disagree on its shape. This is synchronization across representations. The patch inserts a translator, a normalizer, a fromJson, a mapper between two field names. The translator is real work, and it's necessary only because the saved shape and the live shape grew up as two owners of one fact.
The same bug, four times
Line the four up. An await, a subscription, a converter, an extra write. Four fixes, one shape underneath: two owners of one truth, and a patch that restores their agreement without removing the second owner. Every patch did the chore again instead of removing the need for it.
What makes it a tax, not just a recurring mistake: open any of those fixed files and add a new path. Nothing stops you from forgetting an owner. No compiler error. No type that fails. No test. The code is silent. It will let you ship the drift and hear about it from a user. That silence is the cost: the work of keeping the owners agreed has been quietly handed to you, and the system does nothing to help you do it or to tell you when you’ve missed it.
One precision, because it’s where the fair objection lives. “I copy state all the time and it’s fine.” True. A value you derive and never write back, a cache you only ever read, isn’t a second owner; it’s a shadow. The bug needs two places that can each be changed on their own. That’s the dangerous shape: not duplication, but duplication where both copies are writable.
Two things make it worse than an ordinary bug. It’s latent: the inconsistency exists the moment you add the second writable owner, but it stays invisible until some path trips it, so you ship it before you ever see it. Whether the copies actually agree is a runtime fact, so only runtime checks can see it: automated tests or manual QA. What a compiler can’t do is check, at runtime, that two writable copies hold the same value. It can sometimes make the second copy impossible to write in the first place, which is the cure, but it can’t watch two live copies and catch them drifting. And both of those runtime checks only cover the paths they actually run, so the bug hides in the path nobody exercised.
Every fix is correct, and every fix is a band-aid, because the thing that produced the bug, the second owner, is still there, waiting for the next path that forgets the rule. You’re paying a tax, one ticket at a time, and it keeps being charged because the thing that levies it is still in the structure of the code.
What is actually keeping every owner in agreement? Not the compiler, not a type, not a test. You are, on every path, from memory. The architecture has chosen, as its consistency mechanism, a person.
The cure: one owner, derive the rest
So stop paying it. Not “coordinate the owners better.” Remove the second owner.
Three moves do all of it:

• One source of truth. Each fact lives in one place.

• Derive, don’t store. Anything you can compute from the source, compute. Don’t keep a second copy that can drift.

• One way to change it. State changes through a single function, so “how can this change?” has a one-line answer.
None of this is new, and it isn’t mine. It’s the Elm Architecture, a model, an update function, and a view derived from the model, settled more than a decade ago. The shape is the same. Only the names differ.
Watch all three land on one messy fact. You’ve used this control: a date-range picker at the top of a dashboard, every tile and chart below it showing numbers for whatever you pick, with a saved view you can reload. All four bugs live in that one fact, the selected range: it fans out to every widget, a table reads it once at mount, the reload is async, and the saved view stores "last_30_days" where the widgets need a resolved { start, end }.
Now make the range the single source. Every change goes through one update function, even loading a saved view, and everything a widget shows is derived from it.
// The one source: a preset ("last_30_days") or a custom { start, end }.
type DashboardState = { range: RangeSpec };
// One way to change it. Picking a range and loading a saved view both go through here.
function update(state: DashboardState, event: Event): DashboardState {
switch (event.type) {
case "SET_RANGE": return { range: event.range };
case "LOAD_VIEW": return { range: event.saved.range }; // the saved view enters the source, once
default: return assertNever(event); // the compiler makes you handle every case
}
}
// Derive, don't store. Every widget reads the source; none keeps a copy.
const dates = resolveDates(state.range); // "last_30_days" -> { start, end }
revenueTile.show(aggregate(revenueRows, dates)); // a dozen widgets,
ordersChart.show(aggregate(orderRows, dates)); // all reading the
regionTable.show(aggregate(regionRows, dates)); // the same sourcetThe four bugs fall together, for two reasons. Fan-out and missed-sync are gone because no widget holds the range: there is nothing to push it into, and nothing to go stale.
